<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">08 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">East Hollywood (LA County) · Taqueria · True T-49 Reach-In</div>
        <h3>"Back of the cooler is ice cold — front shelves are warm"</h3>
        <p>Evaporator fan motor failure — the classic presentation where the back of the unit near the evaporator stays cold while cold air doesn't circulate to the front. The taqueria had been compensating for weeks by moving temperature-sensitive items to the back shelves without realizing the fan had failed. Product on the front shelves was consistently in the high-40s.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced evaporator fan motor with OEM True part. Tested temperature gradient across all shelf positions — even 37°F front-to-back confirmed within 40 minutes of repair. Also found condenser coils significantly fouled (kitchen grease environment) — cleaned while motor replacement was drying. Enrolled in quarterly maintenance given the kitchen environment. Estimated the fan had been failing for 3–4 weeks based on the motor bearing wear pattern.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Beach (Orange County) · Coastal Restaurant · Beverage-Air Back-Bar Cooler</div>
        <h3>"Wine cooler not holding temp — showing 52°F on a busy Friday night"</h3>
        <p>Refrigerant leak combined with condenser coils clogged enough to prevent adequate heat rejection. The system had been losing refrigerant slowly for weeks — an under-bar location meant the condenser was in a very restricted space behind the bar, accumulating dust and debris at an accelerated rate, plus coastal salt air accelerating fitting corrosion. The combination of reduced charge and degraded condenser performance pushed the unit over its capacity on a high-demand night.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Located refrigerant leak at evaporator fitting, repaired and pressure-tested. Thoroughly cleaned condenser coils — accessible through the rear service panel. Recharged with correct R-134A quantity. Temperature pulled to 38°F within 90 minutes. Bar was able to reopen wine service the same evening. Discussed condenser access and monthly cleaning for this under-bar installation — restricted space + coastal humidity requires more frequent maintenance than an open-access unit in a dry inland environment.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Koreatown (LA County) · Korean Grocery · Turbo Air Prep Table TMP-60SD</div>
        <h3>"Prep table not cooling — meat and banchan prep at 55°F"</h3>
        <p>Compressor location on this Turbo Air prep table is at the bottom, directly on the floor in a busy prep kitchen environment. The condenser was completely blocked with cooking debris — the compressor had tripped its thermal overload due to overheating. The unit was running (fan audible) but the compressor had shut itself off to prevent damage. Product had been at elevated temperature for approximately 4 hours before discovery.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Deep-cleaned condenser coils and housing, reset thermal overload, monitored compressor restart. System pulled down to 37°F within 2 hours. Protein products were marginal — customer made the decision to discard and replace. Raised the prep table on a small platform to improve condenser airflow clearance from the floor — a modification that significantly reduces fouling rate in floor-level prep environments. Now on a 3-month maintenance schedule.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Thousand Oaks (Ventura County) · Natural Grocery · Glass Door Merchandiser</div>
        <h3>"Display case condensation on the glass — product getting wet"</h3>
        <p>Failed anti-sweat heater on the glass door frames — the glass was cold enough to condense ambient humidity because the door frame heater wasn't preventing the surface from dropping to dew point. This is a display-case-specific component. The condensation was affecting product appearance and causing moisture damage to packaging, directly impacting retail sales. Conejo Valley humidity swings between coastal marine layer mornings and dry afternoons accelerate dew-point variability.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced anti-sweat heater wiring on all three door frames. Verified glass temperature above dew point at ambient conditions. No condensation within 30 minutes of repair. Also addressed a door gasket on the center door that had compressed flat — replacing it significantly improved the seal and reduced the cooling load that was partially contributing to the glass temperature drop. Product damage stopped immediately.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

